The lex Tullio was preceded by a len Fabia in tte. 66, by which candidates were forbidden to be escorted by a long train of clients and followers (sectatores) : nothing more is known of this law but what is contained in an allusion to itin the speech for Murenam. A similar provision was contained in a senatus consultum lac. 64, when Cicero a few days before the comitia delivered his election speech (oratio in toga candida) against the coalition (coitu) of Catiline and Gaius Antonius, his competitors for the consulship¹⁰⁴.
